{
  "answer": "**I could not locate any Ghalib couplet in the Falsafa corpus matching or closely approximating \"why should I not weep — the world has forgotten me too?\" (or variations like \"main royein kyun na, duniya ne mujhe bhula diya\").**\n\nThe *Diwan-E-Ghalib*[^1] contains 239 ghazals, and searches across English translations for key phrases (\"why ... weep\", \"should I not weep\", \"world has forgotten\", \"weep forgotten\", \"duniya ... ro\", etc.) yielded no direct or thematic hits combining weeping with the world forgetting the speaker.\n\nClose but non-matching examples:\n- Ghazal 33: \"We'll weep a thousand times—why should a soul be slain?\" and later \"Why all this bitter weeping?\"—references weeping and worldly tasks, but no \"forgotten\" or world-forgetting.[^2]\n- Ghazal 102: \"To be forgotten is the cross I gain is mine.\"—mentions being forgotten, but no weeping.[^3]\n- Ghazal 73: \"Should you have forgotten me, let me remind you...\"—personal forgetting, no weeping or world.[^4]\n\nThis specific couplet may come from a different edition, unattributed source, or loose paraphrase not present here. The corpus covers the standard *Diwan*, but not every variant or minor poem.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [metadata](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/metadata/).\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, Chapter 33, [paragraphs](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/translation/#p-d9d50d).\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, Chapter 102, [paragraphs](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/102-kab-woh-sunta-hai-kahani-meri/translation/#p-8d8ade).\n[^4]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, Chapter 73, [paragraphs](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/73-hui-taakhir-to-kuch-baais-e-taakhir-bhi-tha/translation/#p-85cc4e).",
